President Barack Obama has proclaimed October 15, 2013, as Blind Americans Equality Day. In his proclamation, he highlights the important role blind and visually impaired individuals play in American life and culture. The proclamation emphasizes the commitment of the administration to advancing opportunities for people with disabilities through the Americans with Disabilities Act and other avenues. It mentions the United States' participation in a treaty to expand access to information for visually impaired individuals and the signing of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities. The Department of Education's guidance on the use of Braille as a literacy tool is also highlighted, with a focus on creating equal opportunities for students with disabilities. The proclamation encourages public officials, business and community leaders, educators, librarians, and Americans across the country to observe Blind Americans Equality Day with appropriate ceremonies, activities, and programs.